          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">t (8; 21) </span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">An elderly male with dragging sensation in abdomen presents in the OPD. His cell count had elevated total leucocyte count and increased platelet count. His peripheral smear shows metamyelocytes, myelocytes, eosinophilia and basophilia (image given for reference). Which of the following is the likely genetic anomaly present in this individual? </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/24/picture7_WdmXOwZ.jpg\" style=\"height:194px; width:300px\" /></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6747004",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32031,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A. t (9; 22)</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The<strong> increased cell count (leucocytes and platelets) </strong>with peripheral smear showing <strong>metamyelocytes, myelocytes, eosinophilia and basophilia (mixed myeloid lineage) </strong>is suggestive of a diagnosis of <strong>chronic myeloid leukemia</strong>. Two other features also fit in the diagnosis: </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Age of the patient (peak incidence in 5/6th decade of life) </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The dragging sensation (can be due to splenomegaly seen in CML patients) </span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: t (15;17)</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: is associated with<strong> acute promyelocytic leukemia (APL).</strong> It involves the fusion of the<strong> PML (promyelocytic</strong> <strong>leukemia) gene on chromosome 15 with the RARA (retinoic acid receptor alpha) gene on chromosome 17</strong>, resulting in the <strong>PML-RARA fusion gene.</strong> This fusion gene plays a crucial role in the pathogenesis of APL.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C: t (8;14)</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: is associated with <strong>Burkitt&#39;s lymphoma.</strong> It involves the<strong> c-MYC gene on chromosome 8 </strong>and the <strong>immunoglobulin</strong> <strong>heavy chain gene on chromosome 14</strong>. The dysregulation of <strong>c-MYC</strong>, a proto-oncogene, contributes to the <strong>rapid and uncontrolled</strong> <strong>proliferation of B cells</strong> in Burkitt&#39;s lymphoma.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D: t (8;21)</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: is associated with <strong>acute myeloid leukemia (AML)</strong>, particularly the subtype known as <strong>AML with t(8;21), </strong>also called <strong>AML-M2. </strong>It involves the fusion of the <strong>AML1 (acute myeloid leukemia 1) gene on chromosome 21 with the ETO (eight-twenty-one) gene on chromosome 8, </strong>resulting in the <strong>AML1-ETO fusion gene.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The<strong> genetic anomaly </strong>likely present in an <strong>elderly male </strong>with an<strong> elevated leukocyte and platelet count</strong>, peripheral smear showing <strong>metamyelocytes, myelocytes, eosinophilia, and basophilia is t (9;22), </strong>which is associated with <strong>chronic myeloid leukemia (CML).</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">(Ref: Robbins 10th/e p622) </span></span></em></strong></p>",
