          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Myelodysplastic syndrome </span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A peripheral smear with increased neutrophils, basophils, eosinophils, and platelets is highly suggestive of:</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2152030",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32030,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C. Chronic myelogenous leukemia </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Chronic Myelogenous Leukemia (CML):</strong> is characterized by the presence of the<strong> Philadelphia chromosome</strong>, resulting in the constitutive activation of the <strong>BCR-ABL1 tyrosine kinase</strong>. This leads to<strong> increased production of myeloid cells,</strong> including <strong>neutrophils,</strong> <strong>basophils, eosinophils, and platelets.</strong> The peripheral smear in CML often shows a <strong>&quot;left-shift,&quot; </strong>with <strong>increased mature and immature myeloid cells</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong> Acute Myeloid Leukemia (AML):</strong> is characterized by the <strong>rapid growth </strong>of <strong>abnormal myeloid cells </strong>in the bone marrow. While AML may show <strong>increased myeloid cells </strong>in the peripheral smear, it typically presents with<strong> blasts and a decrease in mature cells</strong>, unlike the broad spectrum of increased cells seen in the question.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong> Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL):</strong> <strong>primarily affects lymphoid cells</strong>. It is characterized by the presence of <strong>lymphoblasts </strong>in the peripheral blood. The question describes an increase in myeloid cell lineages (neutrophils, basophils, eosinophils, and platelets), making ALL less likely.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Myelodysplastic Syndrome (MDS):</strong> is a<strong> group of disorders </strong>characterized by <strong>ineffective hematopoiesis</strong>. While MDS can present with<strong> cytopenias and dysplastic </strong>changes in blood cells, the specific pattern described in the question (increased neutrophils, basophils, eosinophils, and platelets) is more indicative of CML.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Chronic myeloid leukemia </strong>is a<strong> stem cell disease</strong> that is characterized by <strong><em>leukocytosis with granulocytic immaturities, basophilia, splenomegaly</em></strong> and distinct chromosomal abnormality<strong> Philadelphia chromosome</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><em><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">(Ref: Robbins 10<sup>th</sup>/ 622) </span></span></em></strong></p>",
