          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Immunophenotyping</span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 61459,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">FISH in the peripheral blood smear </span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A male patient with splenomegaly with myeloid hyperplasia. What&rsquo;s is the next best investigation to be done?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2640566",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32032,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D. FISH in the peripheral blood smear</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong> </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH) </strong>is a <strong>molecular cytogenetic </strong>technique that can be applied to detect <strong>specific genetic abnormalities </strong>and is invaluable for diagnosis of <strong>CML </strong>(more likely from the history given in the question). </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Whole-body<strong> PET CT (Positron Emission Tomography with Computed Tomography) </strong>is a valuable imaging tool, particularly in the evaluation of <strong>lymphomas and solid tumors. </strong>However, it may <strong>not be the first-line investigation for myeloid hyperplasia </strong>or diseases<strong> primarily </strong>involving the <strong>bone marrow.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Leucocyte alkaline phosphatase (LAP) </strong>is an <strong>enzyme </strong>that can be measured <strong>to assess the activity of neutrophils</strong>. <strong>Low LAP </strong>scores may be associated with conditions like<strong> chronic myeloid leukemia (CML). </strong>However, this test alone might not provide a <strong>definitive diagnosis </strong>and is often used in conjunction with other tests.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Immunophenotyping </strong>is a crucial investigation in the context of<strong> hematological disorders</strong>. It involves the analysis of <strong>cell surface markers </strong>on <strong>blood or bone marrow cells </strong>but is more useful for other leukemias like <strong>ALL, AML or CLL. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">For a <strong>male </strong>patient with<strong> splenomegaly and myeloid hyperplasia</strong>, the next best investigation is <strong>Fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH) </strong>in the peripheral blood smear, particularly to detect chromosomal abnormalities such as the<strong> Philadelphia chromosome </strong>in <strong>chronic myeloid leukemia (CML).</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong><em><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">(Ref: Robbins 10th/e p482) </span></span></em></strong></span></span></span></p>",
